node.text:
Sharon Quirk-Silva was interviewed outside of Disneyland today. She shared her thoughts about the Governors decision not to allow theme parks such as Disneyland to reopen until the county has reached the yellow tier. I wasn’t sure if my iPhone was picking up what she was saying so I tried to ensure I reiterated most of what she was saying. Disneyland is pushing hard to reopen. It’ll be interesting to see what happens as this is the first time in Disneyland history that the park has been shut down for such an extensive period of time.
.

node.text:
This is totally outside of the typical content I create and post, but I felt so strongly that this specific scene in the Netflix documentary Schitts Creek Best Wishes, Warmest Regards needed to be shared. Forgive me, you can hear me sniffling and crying as I filmed this. Schitts Creek is one of my favorite shows and has served as a super catalyst for acceptance, love, and positive personification of the LGBTQ+ community. I share some of my own thoughts and feelings (not very eloquently bc I had a hard time NOT crying) after the scene. I absolutely love that I am seeing more and more support LGBTQ+ community, but I also experience a devastating amount of hate on a daily basis. My goal behind our social media has been and will continue to be to offer ppl a small glimpse into our lives as a family in the hopes that we might open a few minds and hearts along the way. Love is love ❤️ And I hope and pray we see more and more queer representation in movies, television shows, books, etc. 🏳️‍🌈✊🏽 @schittscreek @instadanjlevy @annefrances 
.

In honor of pumpkin spice season, Evan is showing off his Fall Back to School look! Peep those adorable @target duds he’s rocking! I know everyone’s been dying to know (not sure why??) if Evan will attend mainstream school or special ed 🏫 As of now, I have decided homeschooling will be the best option for him. That being said, Eli and Ella will be mainstream schooling. Personally, I prefer to focus on each of my kids as individuals and that includes their needs and abilities. What works for one might not work for the other. I want to do what’s right by my children and making tough decisions comes with the territory.

It’s probably better that Evan waits to attend I person school because he would be ANNIHILATING the fashion game up and down that school yard, y’all! 😂 He has been evaluated and does have an IEP, obvs. But I think he would benefit far more from homeschooling this year. Nothing is set in stone and I am the kind of person who re-evaluates these kinds of things regularly.

If you have any must-have educational materials please let me know in the comments below 👇🏽I will need all the help I can get to work with him as best I can for the time being 😊

node.text:
Evan answering our most common questions like the queen (his word not mine) that he is 👑

I have faced some intense criticism (or pure hate in many instances) for allowing Evan to be, well, EVAN. Honestly, I will never understand the backwards mentality of those who so staunchly stand behind the idea that clothing is gendered, it’s impossible for children to identify as something other than the gender they were assigned at birth, or that boys shouldn’t be permitted to wear dresses 🙄

Don’t believe me? Evan asked for his first dress almost 3 years ago. I didn’t bat an eyelash (because I didn’t have any issues with it) and bought him the dress. Like many parents I assumed he’d wear it a few times and maybe get bored. But I was wrong and I am SO glad my first instinct wasn’t to attempt to deter or shame him for it. This is Evan. My “girlboy.” The child who’s changing the way the world views gender, gender expression, and so called gender norms.

His ability to be 100% who he is and give zero f*cks about what other people think inspires me! I wish I could be more like him. There’s a beauty in the way he lives his life…completely free 🕊 It is my genuine hope that by sharing Evan’s story we might make life a little easier for another little boy out there who dreams of being a princess, too 🤗

*I continue to use he/him pronouns because it is EVAN’S choice and Evan’s choice only to change them. Yes, we’ve discussed this. No, he hasn’t stated he prefers anything else. And yes, he’s ok with people using she/her and they/them pronouns as well.*

“Can I go where you go?” ~ Taylor Swift

Today was Eli’s first time back on Disney soil in over a year and a half °o° Magical memories with our Eli will likely be short lived. I hope my children remember every single moment with him. Every laugh. Every smile. All the good times. And especially all the days spent in Disneyland chasing characters, hitting rides, noshing on snacks, and watching the fireworks 🎆 We’ve learned to make each moment count and it felt so good to have him back out with us 💙

EDIT: For those asking, Eli has MULTIPLE diagnoses. Severe cerebral palsy also known as spastic quadriplegia, is his most noticeable and concerning Dx. Eli was HEAVILY alcohol exposed in utero and is honestly lucky to be alive. There are a ton of things doctors have to monitor him for that can end his life. Most common are things like seizures and/or developing water on the brain. There’s a LOT of medical stuff going on with our sweet Eli, but he is happy, healthy (and I will fight tooth and nail to keep it that way), and thriving ❤️‍🔥

node.text:
Autism.

I had my suspicions. I knew the struggles I was experiencing with Ella weren’t typical. I knew something was different. But I hoped. I prayed. I tried to make bargains with God. I told myself the same things all parents say…she’ll grow out of it. It’s just a phase. All kids do it.

But the truth always has a way of reaching the surface. That part of me that wanted to remain in denial finally heard the words I knew were coming…”She has autism, Ms. McLeod.” This is reality. Our reality. Today our lives changed once again. And all it took was one word…

Autism.
